Constructors and Destructors in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)


1. Introduction

Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) allows programmers to create real-world objects using classes. Two important concepts in OOP are constructors and destructors, which help manage the lifecycle of objects.


2. Constructor

A constructor is a special method that is automatically called when an object is created. Its purpose is to initialize the object's attributes and set up any necessary initial state.

In Python: __init__() is used as the constructor.

Key Features:

Automatically called when an object is created.

Can accept parameters to initialize object attributes.

Helps reduce repetitive code.


Example:

class Student:
    def __init__(self, name, age, course):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
        self.course = course

student1 = Student("Giddy", 22, "Information Science")
print(student1.name, student1.age, student1.course)

Types of Constructors:

1. Default Constructor: Takes no parameters (except self).


2. Parameterized Constructor: Takes parameters to initialize object attributes.

3. Destructor

A destructor is a special method that is automatically called when an object is destroyed or deleted. Its purpose is to perform cleanup operations such as releasing memory or closing resources.

In Python: __del__() is used as the destructor.

Key Features:

Called when the object is no longer needed.

Only takes the self parameter.

Less frequently used in Python due to automatic garbage collection.


Example:

class Student:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
        print(f"Student {self.name} created")

    def __del__(self):
        print(f"Student {self.name} destroyed")

s1 = Student("Giddy")
del s1

4. Differences Between Constructor and Destructor

Feature	Constructor (__init__)	Destructor (__del__)

When called	When object is created	When object is destroyed
Purpose	Initialize object attributes	Cleanup resources before destruction
Parameters	Can take arguments	Only self
Frequency	Commonly used	Less common

5. Real-Life Analogy

Constructor: Setting up a new phone (installing apps, setting name, etc.)

Destructor: Switching off and recycling the phone


6. Example in a Student System

class Student:
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
        print(f"{self.name} has joined FSST")

    def __del__(self):
        print(f"{self.name} has left FSST")

s1 = Student("Giddy", 22)
s2 = Student("Lara", 20)
del s1

Output: Giddy has joined FSST Lara has joined FSST Giddy has left FSST


7. Summary

Constructors are used to initialize objects and can take parameters.

Destructors are used to clean up objects and are automatically called when objects are deleted.

Together, they manage the lifecycle of objects in object-oriented programming, ensuring proper initialization and cleanup.